1
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:17,400
{\an8}Ever since you began to build your empire,
you have had a crutch to lean on.

2
00:00:17,480 --> 00:00:19,640
[Michael] <i>Mum, I swear
in the name of Almighty God,</i>

3
00:00:19,720 --> 00:00:21,840
<i>I will take revenge on Tommy Shelby.</i>

4
00:00:21,920 --> 00:00:25,480
That, my friend,
is the finest opium in the world.

5
00:00:25,560 --> 00:00:28,960
Perhaps we can meet after you've
spoken to your wife's uncle, Jack Nelson.

6
00:00:29,040 --> 00:00:31,360
Tommy Shelby wants
to do business with Jack Nelson?

7
00:00:31,440 --> 00:00:33,840
So speak to your uncle
and get me out of here.

8
00:00:33,920 --> 00:00:37,280
If he doesn't want to buy my opium,
I will sell to the East Boston Jews.

9
00:00:37,360 --> 00:00:39,040
It's Ruby, she's not well.

10
00:00:39,120 --> 00:00:40,160
I'm coming home.

11
00:00:46,120 --> 00:00:50,880
[Polly] <i>There will be a war in this family
and one of you will die.</i>

12
00:00:52,280 --> 00:00:55,160
[Michael] <i>You've been too busy
to punish the people who killed her.</i>

13
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:57,160
<i>How is the family?</i>

14
00:01:08,200 --> 00:01:09,239
[Ruby] Daddy!

15
00:01:13,960 --> 00:01:15,600
Hello, Ruby.

16
00:01:15,680 --> 00:01:16,680
[Ruby laughs]

17
00:01:16,760 --> 00:01:17,680
[Tommy] Come here.

18
00:01:18,200 --> 00:01:21,760
Let me see you. I missed you.
I missed you.

19
00:01:23,680 --> 00:01:27,040
-That's the Black Madonna. [kisses]
-[Charles] What presents did you get us?

20
00:01:27,120 --> 00:01:28,080
[Tommy] Son.

21
00:01:29,640 --> 00:01:32,440
She's all better, Tommy.
You came back for nothing.

22
00:01:36,240 --> 00:01:37,520
But I'm glad you're back.

23
00:01:39,680 --> 00:01:43,400
Right, before we do anything else,
we're going to go out for a drive.

24
00:01:43,480 --> 00:01:45,480
-Okay? Let's go.
-What about me?

25
00:01:45,560 --> 00:01:47,560
Yeah, you come too. Come on.

26
00:01:47,640 --> 00:01:48,680
A drive where?

27
00:01:49,800 --> 00:01:52,240
I've asked the driver
to take us to see Dr Robert.

28
00:01:52,320 --> 00:01:54,200
-To have a look at Ruby.
-Why?

29
00:01:54,280 --> 00:01:57,560
The appointment is in one hour.
You can stay here or you can come.

30
00:01:58,720 --> 00:01:59,680
Right.

31
00:02:01,320 --> 00:02:02,680
[Tommy] Right. Let's go.

32
00:02:22,480 --> 00:02:24,040
[children playing]

33
00:02:40,840 --> 00:02:41,760
[grunts]

34
00:02:42,920 --> 00:02:44,320
[gags and spits]

35
00:02:45,560 --> 00:02:46,600
[coughs]

36
00:02:50,240 --> 00:02:52,680
[door creaks open and shuts]

37
00:02:52,760 --> 00:02:53,680
[Lizzie] Tommy?

38
00:02:54,760 --> 00:02:55,680
Yeah?

39
00:02:58,120 --> 00:03:00,560
It was all good. Everything was clear.

40
00:03:00,640 --> 00:03:01,800
[exhales]

41
00:03:01,880 --> 00:03:03,120
That is a relief.

42
00:03:04,520 --> 00:03:06,080
-That's a relief.
-Yeah.

43
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:09,360
-Driver's bringing the car around.
-[Ruby] Dad.

44
00:03:11,520 --> 00:03:12,520
[Lizzie] Hiya.

45
00:03:15,840 --> 00:03:16,880
Come here.

46
00:03:23,520 --> 00:03:24,760
When did you last sleep?

47
00:03:27,280 --> 00:03:29,440
Not much since we last spoke on the phone.

48
00:03:30,960 --> 00:03:33,400
Now you know Ruby is all clear,
you can sleep.

49
00:03:33,480 --> 00:03:34,480
Yeah.

50
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:40,320
Lizzie, I'm very happy
that Ruby's results are clear.

51
00:03:40,840 --> 00:03:42,480
But still you won't sleep.

52
00:03:44,160 --> 00:03:47,000
I will speak to Johnny
and I will speak to Esmeralda.

53
00:03:47,080 --> 00:03:48,120
[sighs]

54
00:03:52,320 --> 00:03:54,280
[sighs] We could be on holiday.

55
00:03:55,440 --> 00:03:57,320
We could be up a mountain in America.

56
00:03:58,560 --> 00:04:00,240
That wouldn't have been possible.

57
00:04:01,120 --> 00:04:04,880
The man I'm dealing with
is coming to London. I need to be there.

58
00:04:05,440 --> 00:04:07,280
[exhales] No escape.

59
00:04:08,920 --> 00:04:10,400
We will escape, Lizzie.

60
00:04:10,960 --> 00:04:12,400
One last deal to be done.

61
00:04:13,120 --> 00:04:14,080
It'll be difficult.

62
00:04:14,160 --> 00:04:16,200
-[Lizzie sighs]
-Difficulties are to be expected.

63
00:04:16,280 --> 00:04:18,840
This is why I must move from item to item.

64
00:04:24,279 --> 00:04:25,360
Do you feel that?

65
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:27,560
Do you feel anything?

66
00:04:29,160 --> 00:04:32,320
You know, you talk as if
you're watching everything on a screen.

67
00:04:36,560 --> 00:04:40,480
When we go home... When we go home,
we'll give the kids to Frances,

68
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:42,320
and then you and me will go to bed.

69
00:04:43,840 --> 00:04:45,840
And I will be the next item.

70
00:04:46,560 --> 00:04:48,680
-That's how it feels now, Tommy.
-[sighs] Yeah.

71
00:04:48,760 --> 00:04:50,200
Everything on a list.

72
00:04:56,240 --> 00:04:58,200
-Hey, baby.
-[Ruby] When are we going home?

73
00:05:02,840 --> 00:05:04,040
[thunder rumbling]

74
00:05:07,720 --> 00:05:08,560
[glass shatters]

75
00:05:09,040 --> 00:05:10,360
[thunder cracks]

76
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:20,720
[Lizzie] Tommy? Tommy?

77
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:24,040
[both grunting]

78
00:05:34,640 --> 00:05:36,560
[Lizzie] Tommy? Tommy, what's happened?

79
00:05:37,400 --> 00:05:41,240
Oh, fuck! Fuck! Fuck! Fuck!

80
00:05:41,320 --> 00:05:43,280
-[Tommy grunting]
-Come here, come here.

81
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:44,840
[Tommy gasps]

82
00:05:44,920 --> 00:05:46,240
[Lizzie] What's happening?

83
00:05:48,120 --> 00:05:49,000
<i>Tommy!</i>

84
00:05:54,080 --> 00:05:55,160
-Love.
-[both gasping]

85
00:06:06,640 --> 00:06:07,960
[exhales sharply]

86
00:06:12,480 --> 00:06:18,600
It is four years,
one month, six days, since I had a drink.

87
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:21,360
My head is clear.

88
00:06:23,640 --> 00:06:24,760
I am myself.

89
00:06:27,040 --> 00:06:28,520
Is this the first time?

90
00:06:31,160 --> 00:06:33,360
Once on the ship back. Not as bad.

91
00:06:36,440 --> 00:06:37,440
Tommy.

92
00:06:39,040 --> 00:06:40,800
You need to see a doctor.

93
00:06:42,680 --> 00:06:43,960
I have work to do.

94
00:06:45,280 --> 00:06:46,200
[scoffs]

95
00:06:46,280 --> 00:06:47,880
It's the work that's to blame.

96
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:51,200
The people you meet,
the lies that you tell.

97
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:56,960
We've got to keep going
until this Boston business is done.

98
00:06:58,040 --> 00:06:59,160
Then we rest.

99
00:07:01,040 --> 00:07:03,280
Then we Peaky Blinders fucking rest.

100
00:07:05,800 --> 00:07:06,640
[rain pattering]

101
00:07:07,240 --> 00:07:10,880
[woman] Comrades,
before we end this planning meeting

102
00:07:10,960 --> 00:07:12,520
and send you out into the rain...

103
00:07:12,600 --> 00:07:13,720
[crowd laughing]

104
00:07:13,800 --> 00:07:15,080
...we have a surprise.

105
00:07:16,080 --> 00:07:19,240
He just arrived back
from a trade mission to America.

106
00:07:19,320 --> 00:07:24,240
He came back early and he has insisted
on addressing you volunteers in person.

107
00:07:24,320 --> 00:07:25,280
[crowd exclaims]

108
00:07:25,360 --> 00:07:28,720
[woman] Comrades, your Labour
representative for South Birmingham,

109
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:31,560
-Mr Thomas Shelby, MP, OBE.
-[crowd cheering]

110
00:07:56,200 --> 00:07:57,400
I bring with me,

111
00:07:59,040 --> 00:08:04,360
on the train from London,
a message from Westminster.

112
00:08:05,920 --> 00:08:09,880
No! No, no, no. Not a message.
Not a message.

113
00:08:11,880 --> 00:08:13,840
An instruction, in fact.

114
00:08:13,920 --> 00:08:15,200
[crowd mutters]

115
00:08:16,120 --> 00:08:17,520
You must be silent.

116
00:08:17,600 --> 00:08:19,080
[crowd exclaims]

117
00:08:22,440 --> 00:08:23,920
You must say nothing!

118
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:29,560
Say nothing
about the present situation in this city.

119
00:08:30,960 --> 00:08:32,480
Say nothing about hunger.

120
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:36,880
Say nothing about jobs.
Say nothing about pay.

121
00:08:38,039 --> 00:08:42,159
But those in greener pastures,
they may speak.

122
00:08:42,240 --> 00:08:43,320
[crowd exclaims]

123
00:08:43,400 --> 00:08:45,240
They may raise their voices!

124
00:08:45,320 --> 00:08:46,360
[crowd shouts]

125
00:08:46,440 --> 00:08:49,039
But here in the smoke, you men and women,

126
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:54,160
Irish and Italian and English,
who support the socialist cause...

127
00:08:54,760 --> 00:08:57,520
Even your socialist
cats and dogs and canaries...

128
00:08:57,600 --> 00:08:58,560
[crowd laughs]

129
00:09:00,040 --> 00:09:01,560
You must hush

130
00:09:01,640 --> 00:09:03,080
because the king

131
00:09:04,280 --> 00:09:06,360
and all the king's horses
and all the king's men...

132
00:09:06,440 --> 00:09:07,520
[crowd laughs]

133
00:09:07,600 --> 00:09:08,720
...want you to be silent.

134
00:09:10,600 --> 00:09:14,760
But it is you, my friends,
who must suffer the cuts in wages

135
00:09:14,840 --> 00:09:17,200
-and in welfare and in dignity!
-[crowd exclaims]

136
00:09:17,280 --> 00:09:20,680
And you must not complain
'cause that would be unpatriotic.

137
00:09:21,440 --> 00:09:26,640
You soldiers who have fought in France,
you are traitors if you speak up.

138
00:09:26,720 --> 00:09:31,360
You veterans of their wars
and their booms and their busts,

139
00:09:31,440 --> 00:09:35,040
it is you who must take the blows
and carry the burdens

140
00:09:35,120 --> 00:09:39,120
for the sake of those in greener pastures
who bellow at you...

141
00:09:39,200 --> 00:09:40,280
[slams fist]

142
00:09:41,160 --> 00:09:42,160
"Silence!"

143
00:09:42,240 --> 00:09:43,560
[crowd yells]

144
00:09:44,400 --> 00:09:45,880
Well, watch this, comrades.

145
00:09:46,520 --> 00:09:48,040
I will not be silent.

146
00:09:48,120 --> 00:09:49,000
[man] Never again.

147
00:09:49,080 --> 00:09:50,480
Not this Englishman.

148
00:09:50,560 --> 00:09:52,600
[crowd exclaims and cheers]

149
00:09:58,400 --> 00:10:00,280
No silence from me!

150
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:04,080
No silence from me
because I have heard your voices

151
00:10:04,160 --> 00:10:08,600
when you come to me and tell me
about the cries of your hungry children.

152
00:10:10,080 --> 00:10:13,280
And I will gather up
every single one of those cries

153
00:10:13,360 --> 00:10:17,280
and I will take 'em with me
on the train back to Westminster.

154
00:10:18,200 --> 00:10:21,280
And I will let 'em out of the bag
in the House of Commons,

155
00:10:21,360 --> 00:10:23,680
and let them try and silence that, eh?

156
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:25,640
[crowd cheers]

157
00:10:40,560 --> 00:10:43,520
[Tommy] Shouldn't that involve
some sharing of the burden?

158
00:10:44,720 --> 00:10:47,480
All of us taking
a smaller slice of the cake, eh?

159
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:50,800
After all, it's bloody us
who bakes the cake

160
00:10:51,400 --> 00:10:53,960
and makes the cars and melts the metal.

161
00:10:55,160 --> 00:10:57,280
And the king, remember him?

162
00:10:58,400 --> 00:11:02,640
The man who ordered all of this.
Shouldn't he be taking some of the cuts?

163
00:11:03,680 --> 00:11:06,520
Some of the blows? Some of the pain?

164
00:11:07,360 --> 00:11:08,600
No or yes?

165
00:11:08,680 --> 00:11:09,800
[crowd exclaims] Yes!

166
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:22,560
-[shushes]
-[exclaiming stops]

167
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:24,560
Hush, you working men and women.

168
00:11:25,240 --> 00:11:26,440
Silence.

169
00:11:29,160 --> 00:11:30,160
Good.

170
00:11:31,080 --> 00:11:32,240
Save your voices.

171
00:11:33,840 --> 00:11:35,360
You're gonna need 'em

172
00:11:35,440 --> 00:11:39,560
on Saturday when we rally together,
at the Bull Ring Market!

173
00:11:39,640 --> 00:11:40,480
[crowd cheering]

174
00:11:40,560 --> 00:11:45,760
And together we will raise the roof,
break the damned silence,

175
00:11:47,880 --> 00:11:50,440
and bring down this broken government!

176
00:11:50,520 --> 00:11:52,000
[crowd cheering]

177
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:59,720
[chanting] Tommy! Tommy! Tommy! Tommy!

178
00:12:06,760 --> 00:12:07,680
Thank you.

179
00:12:11,040 --> 00:12:12,200
Laura McKee.

180
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:18,360
-Battalion Commander, Fermanagh, IRA.
-You missed the first and second act.

181
00:12:18,440 --> 00:12:21,120
-[woman] Thank you for coming, Mr Shelby.
-Thank you.

182
00:12:21,200 --> 00:12:22,680
[Laura] The third act was enough.

183
00:12:25,680 --> 00:12:29,880
You both have reasons to hate me and to
want to seek revenge for the killing...

184
00:12:29,960 --> 00:12:30,840
[shushes]

185
00:12:33,280 --> 00:12:34,520
Gypsy tradition.

186
00:12:36,160 --> 00:12:40,560
We do not mention the name
of the dead in company.

187
00:12:46,040 --> 00:12:51,720
Laura McKee, in the Shelby family,
business comes before issues of vengeance.

188
00:12:52,560 --> 00:12:55,640
Our beloved departed
would understand and approve.

189
00:12:57,440 --> 00:12:58,960
Let's go, boys.

190
00:12:59,040 --> 00:13:01,280
Our agreement was
we meet in a crowded place.

191
00:13:01,360 --> 00:13:02,680
No need for crowds.

192
00:13:03,880 --> 00:13:05,000
We need you alive.

193
00:13:07,720 --> 00:13:08,640
After you.

194
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:36,560
You know, Mr Shelby, even though
we've been doing business for a while,

195
00:13:37,080 --> 00:13:38,560
we've never met in person.

196
00:13:40,040 --> 00:13:43,680
You spoke with passion and compassion.

197
00:13:46,120 --> 00:13:47,760
You understand forgiveness.

198
00:13:48,880 --> 00:13:50,120
And you drink water.

199
00:13:52,120 --> 00:13:55,080
Yet I heard from many reliable sources

200
00:13:55,160 --> 00:13:58,840
that you have a reputation
for moral turpitude.

201
00:13:59,960 --> 00:14:01,720
[chuckles and clicks tongue]

202
00:14:02,400 --> 00:14:03,720
"Moral turpitude."

203
00:14:05,640 --> 00:14:07,600
It's a good name for a racehorse.

204
00:14:08,760 --> 00:14:11,240
-You don't know what it means?
-I know what it means.

205
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:13,520
It means you fuck people.

206
00:14:14,840 --> 00:14:16,960
Fuck people over. Don't give a fuck.

207
00:14:17,760 --> 00:14:20,720
It means you covet and steal
and burn all principles

208
00:14:20,800 --> 00:14:22,440
for the sake of self-interest.

209
00:14:24,440 --> 00:14:29,520
Well, I'm changing, Laura McKee.
And my organisation is also changing.

210
00:14:34,560 --> 00:14:36,200
So what happened in Boston?

211
00:14:37,280 --> 00:14:38,560
Jack Nelson said no.

212
00:14:39,360 --> 00:14:42,480
Are we accepting "no" as an answer?

213
00:14:44,240 --> 00:14:45,240
These are letters...

214
00:14:45,320 --> 00:14:46,160
[clears throat]

215
00:14:46,760 --> 00:14:50,240
...written to and by Jack Nelson
over the last three months.

216
00:15:03,520 --> 00:15:04,480
This...

217
00:15:05,920 --> 00:15:09,120
This is a private letter
from the president of the United States.

218
00:15:10,400 --> 00:15:12,000
Where the fuck did you get this?

219
00:15:12,080 --> 00:15:12,920
[Tommy sighs]

220
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:17,880
My racehorse "Moral Turpitude"
is just one of many in my stables.

221
00:15:18,520 --> 00:15:21,000
Sometimes, even now,
I'll take her out for a run,

222
00:15:21,680 --> 00:15:24,240
if there is a good cause
that requires her services.

223
00:15:29,080 --> 00:15:30,760
Jack Nelson's coming to London.

224
00:15:31,760 --> 00:15:35,240
Officially, he's coming
to buy liquor import licences.

225
00:15:36,240 --> 00:15:38,520
Unofficially, he's on
a fact-finding mission.

226
00:15:40,080 --> 00:15:43,360
He's coming to measure the strength
of support for fascism in Britain.

227
00:15:43,440 --> 00:15:45,320
He'll report back to the president.

228
00:15:48,240 --> 00:15:49,640
And how does that help us?

229
00:15:52,920 --> 00:15:54,320
In this letter to his son,

230
00:15:55,560 --> 00:15:58,240
Jack Nelson expresses
strong support for fascism.

231
00:15:59,080 --> 00:16:00,000
In this letter,

232
00:16:01,080 --> 00:16:06,680
to a friend in Berlin, he says
some interesting things about Jews.

233
00:16:09,120 --> 00:16:11,200
He's not coming to Europe to find facts.

234
00:16:11,920 --> 00:16:14,480
He's coming to find proof
that fascism will prevail.

235
00:16:16,080 --> 00:16:20,320
And you and I
are going to help him in that task.

236
00:16:24,360 --> 00:16:25,960
I thought you were a socialist.

237
00:16:28,120 --> 00:16:29,120
[inhales]

238
00:16:29,640 --> 00:16:32,640
Well, since I've entered politics,

239
00:16:32,720 --> 00:16:37,440
I've learned that the line doesn't go out
from the middle to the left and the right.

240
00:16:37,520 --> 00:16:38,720
It goes in a circle.

241
00:16:40,080 --> 00:16:41,120
I'll show you.

242
00:16:44,800 --> 00:16:46,320
You go far enough left,

243
00:16:47,200 --> 00:16:50,440
eventually, you'll meet someone
who's gone far enough right

244
00:16:50,520 --> 00:16:52,040
to get to the same place.

245
00:16:54,840 --> 00:16:58,160
Working-class socialists like me,
working-class nationalists like you.

246
00:16:58,760 --> 00:16:59,840
The result...

247
00:17:00,560 --> 00:17:01,800
National Socialism.

248
00:17:04,080 --> 00:17:05,240
And that's me.

249
00:17:06,960 --> 00:17:08,080
In the middle.

250
00:17:09,599 --> 00:17:14,000
Just a man trying to make
an honest living in a very dark world.

251
00:17:18,359 --> 00:17:20,440
You have friends in Dublin, Laura McKee,

252
00:17:21,160 --> 00:17:23,680
who are actively fighting
for a fascist Ireland.

253
00:17:24,520 --> 00:17:27,480
And you are acting
on their behalf, ain't you?

254
00:17:29,440 --> 00:17:32,160
When Jack Nelson comes to London,

255
00:17:32,720 --> 00:17:37,960
I can give him access to Oswald Mosley
